Add coverage for **GlobalExceptionHandler** and the exception classes indirectly through it.

## 1. Create test controller for exceptions

Location:

```text
src/test/java/com/bnpp/pf/partner/repository/controller/GlobalExceptionHandlerTest.java
```

```java
package com.bnpp.pf.partner.repository.controller;

import com.bnpp.pf.partner.repository.exception.AppNotFoundException;
import com.bnpp.pf.partner.repository.exception.SalesPointNotFoundException;
import com.bnpp.pf.partner.repository.exception.UserNotFoundException;
import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;
import org.springframework.http.MediaType;
import org.springframework.test.web.servlet.MockMvc;
import org.springframework.test.web.servlet.setup.MockMvcBuilders;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.GetMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RestController;

import static org.springframework.test.web.servlet.request.MockMvcRequestBuilders.get;
import static org.springframework.test.web.servlet.result.MockMvcResultMatchers.*;

class GlobalExceptionHandlerTest {

    private final MockMvc mockMvc = MockMvcBuilders
            .standaloneSetup(new TestController())
            .setControllerAdvice(new GlobalExceptionHandler())
            .build();

    @Test
    void shouldHandleIllegalArgumentException() throws Exception {
        mockMvc.perform(get("/test/bad-request"))
                .andExpect(status().isBadRequest())
                .andExpect(content().contentTypeCompatibleWith(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON))
                .andExpect(jsonPath("$.message").value("Invalid request"));
    }

    @Test
    void shouldHandleAppNotFoundException() throws Exception {
        mockMvc.perform(get("/test/app-not-found"))
                .andExpect(status().isNotFound())
                .andExpect(jsonPath("$.status").value(404))
                .andExpect(jsonPath("$.error").value("APP_NOT_FOUND"))
                .andExpect(jsonPath("$.message").value("App not found: B2BOOST_BE"));
    }

    @Test
    void shouldHandleUserNotFoundException() throws Exception {
        mockMvc.perform(get("/test/user-not-found"))
                .andExpect(status().isNotFound())
                .andExpect(jsonPath("$.status").value(404))
                .andExpect(jsonPath("$.error").value("USER_NOT_FOUND"))
                .andExpect(jsonPath("$.message").value("User not found: testuser"));
    }

    @Test
    void shouldHandleSalesPointNotFoundException() throws Exception {
        mockMvc.perform(get("/test/sales-point-not-found"))
                .andExpect(status().isNotFound())
                .andExpect(jsonPath("$.status").value(404))
                .andExpect(jsonPath("$.error").value("SALES_POINT_NOT_FOUND"))
                .andExpect(jsonPath("$.message").value("Sales point not found: SP001"));
    }

    @RestController
    static class TestController {

        @GetMapping("/test/bad-request")
        void badRequest() {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Invalid request");
        }

        @GetMapping("/test/app-not-found")
        void appNotFound() {
            throw new AppNotFoundException("B2BOOST_BE");
        }

        @GetMapping("/test/user-not-found")
        void userNotFound() {
            throw new UserNotFoundException("testuser");
        }

        @GetMapping("/test/sales-point-not-found")
        void salesPointNotFound() {
            throw new SalesPointNotFoundException("SP001");
        }
    }
}
```

## 2. Small improvement to your handler

Your `IllegalArgumentException` currently returns only:

```json
{
  "message": "..."
}
```

That is okay, but for consistency I’d change it to:

```java
@ExceptionHandler(IllegalArgumentException.class)
@ResponseStatus(HttpStatus.BAD_REQUEST)
public Map<String, Object> handleIllegalArgumentException(IllegalArgumentException exception) {
    return Map.of(
            STATUS, 400,
            ERROR, "BAD_REQUEST",
            MESSAGE, exception.getMessage()
    );
}
```

Then update the first test to also check:

```java
.andExpect(jsonPath("$.status").value(400))
.andExpect(jsonPath("$.error").value("BAD_REQUEST"))
```

This gives coverage for:

```text
AppNotFoundException
UserNotFoundException
SalesPointNotFoundException
IllegalArgumentException
GlobalExceptionHandler
```
---------------------------------------

For simple exception classes like these, you usually **don’t need separate tests** if they are already covered through:

```text
GlobalExceptionHandlerTest
UserServiceTest
AppConfigServiceTest
```

But if your coverage tool is asking for them explicitly, add a small unit test.

## Exception class test

Location:

```text
src/test/java/com/bnpp/pf/partner/repository/exception/ExceptionTest.java
```

```java
package com.bnpp.pf.partner.repository.exception;

import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;

import static org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat;

class ExceptionTest {

    @Test
    void userNotFoundException_shouldContainExpectedMessage() {
        UserNotFoundException exception = new UserNotFoundException("testuser");

        assertThat(exception.getMessage())
                .isEqualTo("User not found: testuser");
    }

    @Test
    void salesPointNotFoundException_shouldContainExpectedMessage() {
        SalesPointNotFoundException exception =
                new SalesPointNotFoundException("SP001");

        assertThat(exception.getMessage())
                .isEqualTo("Sales point not found: SP001");
    }

    @Test
    void appNotFoundException_shouldContainExpectedMessage() {
        AppNotFoundException exception =
                new AppNotFoundException("B2BOOST_BE");

        assertThat(exception.getMessage())
                .isEqualTo("App not found: B2BOOST_BE");
    }
}
```

That is enough.

No need to over-test these classes; they only wrap a message.
